---
layout: post
title: Physical Fitness Tests and Standards in Army
---

Can you pass physical fitness tests in various countries? Do you match military fitness standards? In this post are described various physical fitness tests and standards used around the World.

<p>
In this post the physical fitness tests of several armies are presented. And at the end of the post is conlusion of common trends in design of such a tests today.
</p>

<h2>Tests by Countries</h2>

<h3>United States Army Physical Fitness Test</h3>

The US army uses the Army Physical Fitness Test (APFT) according to the FM 7-22 Army Physical Readiness Training (<a href="http://www.lsu.edu/hss/milsci/resources/fm7_22.pdf">see</a>).
Soldiers are evaluated based on their performance in three events:
<ul>
    <li><span class="emp">Push-ups</span> (lower position - upper arms at least parralel to the ground)</li>
    <li><span class="emp">Sit-ups</span> (with ankles holded by another person)</li>
    <li><span class="emp">2-mile run</span></li>
</ul> 
In following tables are shown the minimum required scores to pass the test and the maximal possible score. To pass the test, you have to pass all three events. The minimal requirement for all events are shown in following table.

